"Sáenz-Romero C., Rehfeldt G.E., Crookston N.L., Duval P., St-Amant R., Beaulieu J., Richardson B.A.","Spline models of contemporary, 2030, 2060 and 2090 climates for Mexico and their use in understanding climate-change impacts on the vegetation",2010,"Climatic Change","102","3",,"595","623",,,10.1007/s10584-009-9753-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77149155121&partnerID=40&md5=7ea4bff030311cd630c7fb9a7e7d6c15","Instituto de Investigaciones Agropecuarias y Forestales, Universidad Michoacana de San Nicolás de Hidalgo (IIAF-UMSNH), Km 9.5 Carretera Morelia-Zinapécuaro, Tarímbaro, Michoacán 58880, Mexico; Forestry Sciences Laboratory, Rocky Mountain Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 1221 S. Main, Moscow, ID 83843, United States; Centre de foresterie des Laurentides, Service canadien des forêts, Ressources naturelles Canada, 1055 rue du P.E.P.S., CP 10380 Succ. Sainte-Foy, Québec, QC G1V 4C7, Canada; Centre canadien sur la fibre de bois, Service canadien des forêts, Ressources naturelles Canada, 1055 rue du P.E.P.S., CP 10380 Succ. Sainte-Foy, Québec, QC G1V 4C7, Canada; Forestry Sciences Laboratory, Rocky Mountain Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 735 North 500 East, Provo, UT, United States","Sáenz-Romero, C., Instituto de Investigaciones Agropecuarias y Forestales, Universidad Michoacana de San Nicolás de Hidalgo (IIAF-UMSNH), Km 9.5 Carretera Morelia-Zinapécuaro, Tarímbaro, Michoacán 58880, Mexico; Rehfeldt, G.E., Forestry Sciences Laboratory, Rocky Mountain Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 1221 S. Main, Moscow, ID 83843, United States; Crookston, N.L., Forestry Sciences Laboratory, Rocky Mountain Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 1221 S. Main, Moscow, ID 83843, United States; Duval, P., Centre de foresterie des Laurentides, Service canadien des forêts, Ressources naturelles Canada, 1055 rue du P.E.P.S., CP 10380 Succ. Sainte-Foy, Québec, QC G1V 4C7, Canada; St-Amant, R., Centre de foresterie des Laurentides, Service canadien des forêts, Ressources naturelles Canada, 1055 rue du P.E.P.S., CP 10380 Succ. Sainte-Foy, Québec, QC G1V 4C7, Canada; Beaulieu, J., Centre canadien sur la fibre de bois, Service canadien des forêts, Ressources naturelles Canada, 1055 rue du P.E.P.S., CP 10380 Succ. Sainte-Foy, Québec, QC G1V 4C7, Canada; Richardson, B.A., Forestry Sciences Laboratory, Rocky Mountain Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 735 North 500 East, Provo, UT, United States","Spatial climate models were developed for México and its periphery (southern USA, Cuba, Belize and Guatemala) for monthly normals (1961-1990) of average, maximum and minimum temperature and precipitation using thin plate smoothing splines of ANUSPLIN software on ca. 3,800 observations. The fit of the model was generally good: the signal was considerably less than one-half of the number of observations, and reasonable standard errors for the surfaces would be less than 1°C for temperature and 10-15% for precipitation. Monthly normals were updated for three time periods according to three General Circulation Models and three emission scenarios. On average, mean annual temperature would increase 1.5°C by year 2030, 2.3°C by year 2060 and 3.7°C by year 2090; annual precipitation would decrease -6.7% by year 2030, -9.0% by year 2060 and -18.2% by year 2090. By converting monthly means into a series of variables relevant to biology (e. g., degree-days > 5°C, aridity index), the models are directly suited for inferring plant-climate relationships and, therefore, in assessing impact of and developing programs for accommodating global warming. Programs are outlined for (a) assisting migration of four commercially important species of pine distributed in altitudinal sequence in Michoacán State (b) developing conservation programs in the floristically diverse Tehuacán Valley, and (c) perpetuating Pinus chiapensis, a threatened endemic. Climate surfaces, point or gridded climatic estimates and maps are available at http://forest.moscowfsl.wsu.edu/climate/. © 2009 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.",,"Altitudinal sequence; Annual precipitation; Aridity index; Conservation programs; Emission scenario; General circulation model; Guatemala; Me-xico; Mean annual temperatures; Smoothing spline; Standard errors; Thin plate; Time-periods; Global warming; Splines; Climate models; climate change; climate modeling; coniferous tree; emission; endangered species; error analysis; general circulation model; global warming; mapping method; population distribution; precipitation (climatology); software; spatial analysis; species conservation; temperature effect; vegetation type; Mexico [North America]; Michoacan; Puebla [Mexico]; Tehuacan Valley; Pinus chiapensis",,,,,,"Aitken, S.N., Yeaman, S., Holliday, J.A., Wang, T., Curtis-McLane, S., Adaptation, migration or extirpation: climate change outcomes for tree populations (2008) Evol Appl, 1, pp. 95-111; Bates, D., Wahba, G., Computational methods for generalized cross validation with large data sets (1982) Treatment of Integral Equations by Numerical Methods, pp. 283-296. , C. T. H. Baker and G. F. Miller (Eds.), New York: Academic; Beaulieu, J., Perron, M., Bousquet, J., Multivariate patterns of adaptive genetic variation and seed source transfer in black spruce (2004) Can J For Res, 34, pp. 531-545; Beg, N., Morlot, J.C., Davidson, O., Afrane-Okesse, Y., Tyani, L., Denton, F., Sokona, Y., Rahman, A.A., Linkages between climate change and sustainable development (2002) Clim Policy, 2, pp. 129-144; Boer, E.J., de Beurs, K., Hartkamp, A.D., Krigging and thin plate splines for mapping climate variables (2001) Int J Appl Earth Observ Geoinform, 3 (2), pp. 146-154; Breiman, L., Random forests (2001) Mach Learn, 45, pp. 5-32; Brown, D.E., Reichenbacher, F., Franson, S.E., (1998) A Classification of North American Biotic Communities, , Salt Lake City: University of Utah; Christensen, J.H., Hewiston, B., Busuioc, A., Chen, A., Gao, X., Held, I., Jones, R., Whet